text=:Category: PracticeCategory%0a:Title: Tolkien and Why Some Languages Sound Good or Evil%0a:Author: BenP%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 05.02.2021 - 11:35%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210317-174259-48120#%0a* [-17.03.2021 - 10:42-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210317-174259-48120#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aTolkien invented a number of languages for The Lord of the Rings and they all seem to fit their respective characters perfectly.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI know there are a couple of you who are familiar with Tolkien but for those of you who aren't, Tolkien wrote The Lord of the Rings, a fantasy series for which he created a bunch of different languages for all the races in the book.%0a%0aI've always wondered how he managed to make the languages of the evil characters sound unpleasant and almost evil, and the languages of the good characters pleasant and almost musical. The Elves, for example, who are good, sound like this: "I amar prestar aen, han mathon ne nen, han mathon ne chae a han noston ned 'wilith" and the Orcs, who are evil, sound like this: "Ugluk u bagronk sha pushdug Saruman-glob bubhosh skai." These examples aren't great, but I hope you hear what I'm hearing.%0a%0aOff the top of my head, it seems like Orcish has more plosive sounds, which gives it a more choppy sound in general. Elvish uses a lot of "th" and "l" sounds, which are smoother transitions between vowels. That being said, I'm still not sure why short choppy syllables sound more "evil" in this context than smoother sounds.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
